@markusthoemmes @cbickel what do you think about changing this emit in the activation view:

```js
    emit([doc.namespace+PATHSEP+doc.name, doc.start], value);
```

which doesn't permit filtering by a package to extract the package name from the path annotation, and instead:

```js
    let pkg = getPackageFromAnnotation(doc.annotations) || "default"
    emit([doc.namespace+PATHSEP+pkg+PATHSEP+doc.name, doc.start], value);
```

where we prefix the package name if it exists, or "default" to normalize the strings for a missing package.

this will allow matching/filtering on an action either in the default package or a named package (but not a binding, which we dont track in an activation).

i could do that in a subsequent PR since it will involve some CLI sugaring as well pending feedback.

Edit: I investigated a bit more. We wouldn't need 'default' as a prefix. Here's a possible path suffix to add to the view.

```javascript
  var pathFilter = function(doc) {
    for (i = 0; i < doc.annotations.length; i++) {
      var a = doc.annotations[i];
      if (a.key == "path") try {
          var p = a.value.split(PATHSEP);
          if (p.length == 3) {
            return p[1] + PATHSEP + doc.name;
          } else return doc.name;
      } catch (e) {
        return doc.name;
      }
    }
    return doc.name;
  }
```

But as noted before, we lose information about a binding fairly early, so all activations are either wrt to the package name or default package. It would seem off though to have a package indexed activation which may not be a name native to the namespace.

Plus, the API change is a bit more subtle. The filter today is an EntityName, and hence not ambiguous. Should its type change to EntityPath or more strictly a FullyQualifiedEntityPath which is the outward facing type for other APIs dealing with names. The latter is cleanest but then it's an API breaking change, or we have to maintain backward compatibility in the controller (Either[EntityName, FullyQualifiedName] for example). I think we can defer this.

